00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.405
DAVE: I'm pleased to
introduce Peggy Orenstein.

00:00:02.405 --> 00:00:04.580
In addition to being
a bestselling author,

00:00:04.580 --> 00:00:06.244
she's been named
one of the "40 women

00:00:06.244 --> 00:00:08.410
who changed the media
business in the past 40 years"

00:00:08.410 --> 00:00:10.650
by the "Columbia
Journalism Review."

00:00:10.650 --> 00:00:13.580
Her last few books have
focused on topics related

00:00:13.580 --> 00:00:15.730
to her growing daughter,
or are relevant to them,

00:00:15.730 --> 00:00:18.340
and this book continues
in that tradition.

00:00:18.340 --> 00:00:20.610
As the father of
a teenage girl, I

00:00:20.610 --> 00:00:23.915
found the topic both
interesting and concerning.

00:00:23.915 --> 00:00:26.460
Even though I started the
book with my daughter in mind,

00:00:26.460 --> 00:00:28.752
along the way it
gave me insights

00:00:28.752 --> 00:00:30.900
relevant to both of
my children, and I'm

00:00:30.900 --> 00:00:32.750
sure you'll find
it insightful, too.

00:00:32.750 --> 00:00:35.330
Please join me in giving a warm
welcome to Peggy Orenstein.

00:00:35.330 --> 00:00:38.935
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:42.499 --> 00:00:44.290
PEGGY ORENSTEIN: So I
have-- oh, yeah look.

00:00:44.290 --> 00:00:47.030
I've got a microphone on me.

00:00:47.030 --> 00:00:49.530
This is interesting,
because I have yet

00:00:49.530 --> 00:00:56.106
