00:00:58.976 --> 00:01:00.600
I wondered about this
coming to Google,

00:01:00.600 --> 00:01:02.683
because I kind of figured
it was a little bit more

00:01:02.683 --> 00:01:05.280
of a guy place to work, although
that might be a stereotype,

00:01:05.280 --> 00:01:08.010
and I apologize if that's true.

00:01:08.010 --> 00:01:10.800
But I was excited about that.

00:01:10.800 --> 00:01:12.970
So I wanted to talk a
little bit about this book,

00:01:12.970 --> 00:01:16.850
and how I came to do it,
and some of what I found.

00:01:16.850 --> 00:01:20.146
And then I thought
we could just chat

00:01:20.146 --> 00:01:21.270
if that works for you guys.

00:01:21.270 --> 00:01:27.610
So I came to this book
really-- my previous book

00:01:27.610 --> 00:01:30.205
had been called "Cinderella
Ate My Daughter."

00:01:30.205 --> 00:01:35.150
And that was looking at the ways
that the culture was telling

00:01:35.150 --> 00:01:39.690
girls, from the very youngest
ages, that how they looked

00:01:39.690 --> 00:01:42.254
was more important
than who they were.

00:01:42.254 --> 00:01:43.920
And I was looking at
that through a kind

00:01:43.920 --> 00:01:45.840
of pop cultural lens.

00:01:45.840 --> 00:01:50.090
And I was looking at it partly
because I'm a mother myself,

00:01:50.090 --> 00:01:54.110
and I have a 12-- now
12-and-1/2-year-old daughter.

00:01:54.110 --> 00:01:57.350
And after I finished that
book, I was going around,

00:01:57.350 --> 00:01:59.850
and I was starting to hear
some stories that were really

00:01:59.850 --> 00:02:03.100
concerning me about
the hookup culture

00:02:03.100 --> 00:02:07.220
and about sexting and
about binge drinking.

00:02:07.220 --> 00:02:09.973
And my first response
was to kind of go, ooh,

00:02:09.973 --> 00:02:10.930
my child's little.

00:02:10.930 --> 00:02:12.013
I don't have to hear this.

00:02:12.013 --> 00:02:15.036
I don't want to hear this yet.

00:02:15.036 --> 00:02:18.080
Parenting from ignorance
and fear, generally not

00:02:18.080 --> 00:02:19.830
the best idea.

00:02:19.830 --> 00:02:22.845
So I started sort
of digging into it.

00:02:22.845 --> 00:02:26.835
And what I wanted
to look at was,

00:02:26.835 --> 00:02:29.129
we're having this
umbrella conversation

00:02:29.129 --> 00:02:30.670
in this culture
right now that's been

00:02:30.670 --> 00:02:34.910
going on for several years
about assault on campus.

00:02:34.910 --> 00:02:39.906
And it's a really, really,
really important topic.

00:02:39.906 --> 00:02:47.470
But consent, it's a really low
bar for a sexual experience.

00:02:47.470 --> 00:02:51.040
You know, like, I was not
assaulted is a really low bar

00:02:51.040 --> 00:02:53.030
for a sexual experience.

00:02:53.030 --> 00:02:54.700
And so I became
really interested

00:02:54.700 --> 00:02:58.620
in looking at what was going
on in young women's lives

00:02:58.620 --> 00:03:01.860
after yes, and what had
changed, what hadn't, how

00:03:01.860 --> 00:03:05.330
they-- whether they felt more
in control of their experience,

00:03:05.330 --> 00:03:07.940
whether they were more able
to create something that

00:03:07.940 --> 00:03:10.070
was satisfying them,
whether they were more

00:03:10.070 --> 00:03:12.490
able to articulate
their wants, needs,

00:03:12.490 --> 00:03:14.745
and desires than
previous generations,

00:03:14.745 --> 00:03:16.760
and whether some of
the dynamics that

00:03:16.760 --> 00:03:18.600
were happening in
those relationships

00:03:18.600 --> 00:03:21.150
were feeding into
the culture that

00:03:21.150 --> 00:03:26.910
was surfacing around
coercive sex and assault.

00:03:26.910 --> 00:03:31.670
So I decided to talk
to young women who

00:03:31.670 --> 00:03:33.670
were between the
ages of 15 and 20,

00:03:33.670 --> 00:03:35.760
because that's
sort of when girls

00:03:35.760 --> 00:03:37.730
are becoming sexually active.

00:03:37.730 --> 00:03:42.088
And I talked to girls
who were-- they spanned

00:03:42.088 --> 00:03:45.424
a pretty broad
ethnic demographic,

00:03:45.424 --> 00:03:50.120
but they were all middle class,
they were all in high school,

00:03:50.120 --> 00:03:53.270
either going to college
or already in college.

00:03:53.270 --> 00:03:56.280
And I particularly chose that
demographic because I wanted

00:03:56.280 --> 00:03:58.040
to talk to girls
that we think of

00:03:58.040 --> 00:04:00.880
has having opportunity,
and the kind of girls

00:04:00.880 --> 00:04:03.730
that we think of as
being the beneficiaries

00:04:03.730 --> 00:04:05.265
of the feminist movement.

00:04:05.265 --> 00:04:07.436
Because if those
girls who were-- I

00:04:07.436 --> 00:04:08.810
mean, the girls
I talked to, they

00:04:08.810 --> 00:04:10.400
were-- if I had been
interviewing them

00:04:10.400 --> 00:04:13.410
about their education,
their aspirations,

00:04:13.410 --> 00:04:14.960
their professional
dreams, I would

00:04:14.960 --> 00:04:17.540
have walked away so impressed.

00:04:17.540 --> 00:04:21.600
And if these girls who were
leaning in all over the place,

00:04:21.600 --> 00:04:24.890
you know, were toppling
in their personal lives,

00:04:24.890 --> 00:04:27.860
I felt that we couldn't really
deny that there were issues

00:04:27.860 --> 00:04:29.640
that we needed to address.

00:04:29.640 --> 00:04:33.950
And what I found with them was
that while today's young women

00:04:33.950 --> 00:04:38.370
felt entitled to engage
in sexual activity,

00:04:38.370 --> 00:04:41.810
they didn't necessarily
feel entitled to enjoy it.

00:04:41.810 --> 00:04:44.070
So as one young
woman I talked to,

00:04:44.070 --> 00:04:46.940
who is a sophomore at an Ivy
League school said to me,

00:04:46.940 --> 00:04:51.670
you know, I come from
generations of strong women.

00:04:51.670 --> 00:04:55.095
And my grandmother was a
firecracker, and my mother's

00:04:55.095 --> 00:04:58.670
super strong, and my sister
and I are really loud,

00:04:58.670 --> 00:05:01.030
and that's our feminine power.

00:05:01.030 --> 00:05:02.840
And then she proceeded
to articulate

00:05:02.840 --> 00:05:10.640
a kind of series of
hookups that were

00:05:10.640 --> 00:05:13.770
kind of demeaning,
depersonalized, not

00:05:13.770 --> 00:05:16.040
very pleasurable.

00:05:16.040 --> 00:05:20.220
And she said, you know,
I think we girls are just

00:05:20.220 --> 00:05:24.320
socialized to be deferential
and not express our wants.

00:05:24.320 --> 00:05:26.500
And I said, wait.

00:05:26.500 --> 00:05:28.660
Five minutes ago,
you told me that you

00:05:28.660 --> 00:05:30.630
were a really strong woman.

00:05:30.630 --> 00:05:34.566
And she kind of hemmed and hawed
and she said, yeah, you know,

00:05:34.566 --> 00:05:36.940
I don't think anybody ever
told me that that strong woman

00:05:36.940 --> 00:05:39.410
image applied to sex.

00:05:39.410 --> 00:05:43.650
And I began to think about
this disconnect between how

00:05:43.650 --> 00:05:49.440
we talk about sex in the
culture and how we see sex

00:05:49.440 --> 00:05:52.830
all around us, and how
the landscape is littered

00:05:52.830 --> 00:05:55.060
with female body parts
used to sell everything

00:05:55.060 --> 00:05:58.640
that we can possibly think
of, and the complete dearth

00:05:58.640 --> 00:06:03.160
of honest conversation,
frank conversation,

00:06:03.160 --> 00:06:05.350
real, authentic
conversation that we

00:06:05.350 --> 00:06:07.230
have with young
women-- and young men,

00:06:07.230 --> 00:06:10.090
but particularly young
women-- about sex.

00:06:10.090 --> 00:06:15.010
And the whole idea of where
my previous book led me

00:06:15.010 --> 00:06:17.160
to this book-- or
I was saying, girls

00:06:17.160 --> 00:06:19.804
used to talk about
pretty, and how

00:06:19.804 --> 00:06:21.220
it was more important
to be pretty

00:06:21.220 --> 00:06:24.660
than to be anything else,
that had morphed into hot.

00:06:24.660 --> 00:06:28.924
And girls were
sold hot, which is

00:06:28.924 --> 00:06:35.420
a really narrow, superficial,
commercialized idea of what's

00:06:35.420 --> 00:06:38.130
sexy and what's
attractive that tells them

00:06:38.130 --> 00:06:41.930
over and over that how their
bodies look to someone else

00:06:41.930 --> 00:06:45.555
is more important than how
those bodies feel to themselves.

00:06:45.555 --> 00:06:49.450
And they're sold that in a way
that whereas I think parents

00:06:49.450 --> 00:06:54.590
who are Gen-X parents or who
are Baby Boom parents, women

00:06:54.590 --> 00:06:56.490
that age would have
pushed back against that

00:06:56.490 --> 00:06:59.480
as self-objectification
or sexualization.

00:06:59.480 --> 00:07:01.105
For today's young
women, that's sold

00:07:01.105 --> 00:07:05.340
as a source of empowerment
and self-confidence,

00:07:05.340 --> 00:07:09.150
and often is the
most important source

00:07:09.150 --> 00:07:11.190
of self-confidence and power.

00:07:11.190 --> 00:07:13.950
So it becomes much more
complicated for those girls.

00:07:13.950 --> 00:07:17.245
For instance, as one young woman
that I was talking to said,

00:07:17.245 --> 00:07:20.115
she showed me a
picture of herself,

00:07:20.115 --> 00:07:22.610
and she was going
to a party, and she

00:07:22.610 --> 00:07:26.580
had the requisite crop top and
little skirt and high heels.

00:07:26.580 --> 00:07:30.255
And she said, you know,
I'm proud of my body,

00:07:30.255 --> 00:07:33.160
and I never feel more
liberated than when

00:07:33.160 --> 00:07:35.070
I'm wearing skimpy clothing.

00:07:35.070 --> 00:07:37.260
And I said, OK.

00:07:37.260 --> 00:07:39.580
And we talked about
it a little more.

00:07:39.580 --> 00:07:42.520
And a few minutes later, she
said that a year previous,

00:07:42.520 --> 00:07:45.050
she wouldn't have worn that
same outfit because she

00:07:45.050 --> 00:07:46.790
was 25 pounds heavier.

00:07:46.790 --> 00:07:48.384
And as she put it,
some jerky boys

00:07:48.384 --> 00:07:49.800
would have called
me the fat girl,

00:07:49.800 --> 00:07:52.040
and that would be bad
for my mental health.

00:07:52.040 --> 00:07:55.010
So then I felt we needed
to have a discussion,

00:07:55.010 --> 00:07:57.240
and have a discussion
with young girls about who

00:07:57.240 --> 00:07:59.910
gets to be proud of
which bodies under what

00:07:59.910 --> 00:08:03.750
circumstances, and how
liberating that idea of hot

00:08:03.750 --> 00:08:07.360
really is if humiliation
and judgment lurk just

00:08:07.360 --> 00:08:09.420
around the corner.

00:08:09.420 --> 00:08:12.370
And what we know in
the culture of hot

00:08:12.370 --> 00:08:15.260
is that
self-sexualization affects

00:08:15.260 --> 00:08:17.860
girls cognitively,
psychologically,

00:08:17.860 --> 00:08:22.210
and in a real bait-and-switch,
it affects them sexually.

00:08:22.210 --> 00:08:24.370
Girls who
self-sexualize actually

00:08:24.370 --> 00:08:27.730
report less power
in the bedroom,

00:08:27.730 --> 00:08:31.510
less satisfaction, less
control over their experiences.

00:08:31.510 --> 00:08:34.446
So there's this way
that I felt like, OK.

00:08:37.456 --> 00:08:41.530
If the opposite were
true, if this was truly

00:08:41.530 --> 00:08:45.110
creating a more powerful
situation for girls

00:08:45.110 --> 00:08:48.510
in the workplace, in
education, in their sex lives,

00:08:48.510 --> 00:08:50.520
I'd have to say, all right.

00:08:50.520 --> 00:08:53.130
I'm just fusty and old, and
it's time for me to shuffle off,

00:08:53.130 --> 00:08:54.016
you know?

00:08:54.016 --> 00:08:57.310
But it seemed quite
apparent to me

00:08:57.310 --> 00:09:00.450
that the confidence was
coming out with the clothes,

00:09:00.450 --> 00:09:02.240
coming off with the clothes.

00:09:02.240 --> 00:09:05.240
And whether we were
talking about porn,

00:09:05.240 --> 00:09:06.740
whether we were
talking about pop,

00:09:06.740 --> 00:09:09.100
whether we were talking about
fashion, what girls were

00:09:09.100 --> 00:09:12.340
learning was that pleasing
others was more important

00:09:12.340 --> 00:09:14.880
than their own pleasure,
that being desirable

00:09:14.880 --> 00:09:17.120
was more important than
understanding their desire,

00:09:17.120 --> 00:09:21.350
that appearing sexy was more
important than understanding

00:09:21.350 --> 00:09:23.090
their own sexuality.

00:09:23.090 --> 00:09:25.500
And one of the things that
I talk about in the book

00:09:25.500 --> 00:09:31.810
is the way that we
need to, as adults,

00:09:31.810 --> 00:09:34.840
change the way that we
talk about sex with kids

00:09:34.840 --> 00:09:37.300
and broaden our
definition of sex

00:09:37.300 --> 00:09:40.530
beyond virginity and
beyond intercourse.

00:09:40.530 --> 00:09:43.560
Because when we talk about
sex as being intercourse,

00:09:43.560 --> 00:09:46.900
we are-- and in fact, the
rates of intercourse among kids

00:09:46.900 --> 00:09:48.325
have not changed.

00:09:48.325 --> 00:09:49.950
They're sexually
active at the same age

00:09:49.950 --> 00:09:51.980
as they were 20 years
ago, and they're sexually

00:09:51.980 --> 00:09:53.390
active at the same rates.

00:09:53.390 --> 00:09:57.980
However, that denies and
diminishes and marginalizes

00:09:57.980 --> 00:10:00.520
the other forms
of sexual activity

00:10:00.520 --> 00:10:03.510
that are taking place,
particularly oral sex.

00:10:03.510 --> 00:10:05.410
And it makes it so
that those are not

00:10:05.410 --> 00:10:10.000
subject to the same
rules about consent,

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:13.380
coercion, responsibility,
and respect.

00:10:13.380 --> 00:10:16.035
It makes it into not sex.

00:10:16.035 --> 00:10:19.170
So particularly where
oral sex was concerned,

00:10:19.170 --> 00:10:24.470
I heard so many stories
about girls having, you know,

00:10:24.470 --> 00:10:25.000
oral sex.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:27.200
And when I say that,
I mean female on male,

00:10:27.200 --> 00:10:30.410
because male on female was
a whole different situation

00:10:30.410 --> 00:10:31.150
for girls.

00:10:31.150 --> 00:10:33.500
But female and male, they
would describe as not sex.

00:10:33.500 --> 00:10:35.030
That would describe
as no big deal.

00:10:35.030 --> 00:10:37.130
And they engaged in it
for a lot of reasons.

00:10:37.130 --> 00:10:42.810
It was to please a partner,
to gain popularity,

00:10:42.810 --> 00:10:48.620
to feel a sense of
power, to feel desirable,

00:10:48.620 --> 00:10:50.375
because they wanted
an evening to end,

00:10:50.375 --> 00:10:51.750
and they wanted
a guy to go away,

00:10:51.750 --> 00:10:54.290
and they didn't know how
else to make him go away.

00:10:54.290 --> 00:10:57.040
But it was rarely something
that was in their own bodies.

00:10:57.040 --> 00:11:01.040
And after a while, I
started saying to girls,

00:11:01.040 --> 00:11:03.870
because I got sort of
frustrated by hearing

00:11:03.870 --> 00:11:08.670
all these stories of this
one-way situation, what

00:11:08.670 --> 00:11:11.550
if every time you
were alone with a guy,

00:11:11.550 --> 00:11:15.340
he asked you to
go to the kitchen

00:11:15.340 --> 00:11:19.640
and get him a glass of
water, and he never offered

00:11:19.640 --> 00:11:21.560
to get you a glass of water?

00:11:21.560 --> 00:11:23.240
Or if he did, it
was kind of like--

00:11:23.240 --> 00:11:25.740
[SIGH]

00:11:28.240 --> 00:11:32.695
You want me to, you know,
get you a glass of water?

00:11:32.695 --> 00:11:34.400
You know, really begrudging.

00:11:34.400 --> 00:11:36.105
You would never stand for it.

00:11:36.105 --> 00:11:38.150
And they would say--
they would laugh

00:11:38.150 --> 00:11:41.570
and they'd say, well, when
you put it that way, yeah.

00:11:41.570 --> 00:11:44.110
And I said, well, maybe you
need to put it that way.

00:11:44.110 --> 00:11:46.940
Maybe you need to think
about why for you it's

00:11:46.940 --> 00:11:48.990
more insulting to think
about getting somebody

00:11:48.990 --> 00:11:52.520
a glass of water than performing
a nonreciprocal sex act.

00:11:52.520 --> 00:11:55.380
And it wasn't just about
girls getting theirs.

00:11:55.380 --> 00:11:59.431
But I became very
intrigued with this idea

00:11:59.431 --> 00:12:01.750
of what Sara McClelland,
who's a researcher

00:12:01.750 --> 00:12:04.926
of the University of Michigan,
calls intimate justice.

00:12:04.926 --> 00:12:11.950
And just like when
we talk about who

00:12:11.950 --> 00:12:16.050
does the dishes in your home is
partly a political act as well

00:12:16.050 --> 00:12:20.000
as a personal accommodation,
sex has those dynamics too,

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:21.970
and it can bring
up similar ideas

00:12:21.970 --> 00:12:25.550
about equality, economic
disparity, mental health,

00:12:25.550 --> 00:12:26.270
violence.

00:12:26.270 --> 00:12:30.452
And we need to ask, when we
talk about girls and sex,

00:12:30.452 --> 00:12:33.090
who gets to engage
in an experience?

00:12:33.090 --> 00:12:35.690
Who's entitled to enjoy it?

00:12:35.690 --> 00:12:38.350
Who's the primary beneficiary
of that experience?

00:12:38.350 --> 00:12:41.680
And how each partner
defines good enough.

00:12:41.680 --> 00:12:43.590
And those are
really thorny ideas

00:12:43.590 --> 00:12:46.650
to explore for adult
women, I think.

00:12:46.650 --> 00:12:48.970
But when we're talking
about girls' early formative

00:12:48.970 --> 00:12:51.440
experience that's going
to be following them

00:12:51.440 --> 00:12:56.160
through their lives,
you know, I just-- I

00:12:56.160 --> 00:13:00.180
don't want girls' early
experiences to be something

00:13:00.180 --> 00:13:02.402
that they have to get over.

00:13:02.402 --> 00:13:05.940
And that was something that I
was just hearing way too much.

00:13:05.940 --> 00:13:08.390
So as part of that
intimate justice,

00:13:08.390 --> 00:13:11.650
we set girls up to
expect inequality

00:13:11.650 --> 00:13:13.470
in their sexual relationships.

00:13:13.470 --> 00:13:18.830
And I call that the
psychological clitoridectomy,

00:13:18.830 --> 00:13:20.670
that we engage in.

